<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911119-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>911119-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Honda Motor Plans   To Increase Purchases   Of U.S. Auto Parts   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>11/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   HMC</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)AUTOMOBILES (AUT)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Honda Motor Co. said that its purchases ofU.S.-made auto parts and materials will rise to $4.5 billionin the year ending March 31, 1995.   The move follows announcements of similar increases byToyota Motor Corp., Nissan Motor Co. and Mazda Motor Corp.earlier this month, and it comes amid growing friction aboutthe U.S.-Japan bilateral trade imbalance in the automobilesector.</LP><TEXT>   Honda's fiscal 1994 target is to purchase $4.15 billion ofU.S.-made auto parts and materials for its U.S. operations,and $350 million in exports to Japan. Honda bought $2.8billion in U.S.-made parts and materials in the 1990 fiscalyear, and it expects that amount to grow to $3.2 billion inthe current fiscal year.   Honda's purchasing goals include giving preference to U.S.parts suppliers, involving U.S. suppliers in &quot;design-in&quot;activities, expanding North American research and developmentoperations, transferring technology to U.S. parts suppliersand helping U.S. suppliers increase exports to Japan.   The U.S. and Japan began bilateral talks on trade inautomobiles and auto parts this year. The U.S. has said theoverall automobile sector accounts for 75% of the U.S. tradedeficit with Japan, and that progress in reducing thebilateral trade imbalance cannot be made without addressingthe auto sector.</TEXT></DOC>